@samgyeopsaI_ yeah i like how all the characters are presented as morally grey and there’s not a “correct” answer since they all have pros/cons. idk about smtv but until the remake nocturne didnt have a “true” ending so you dont feel like any choice is less valid than the others which is nice

@samgyeopsaI_ i havent played smtv yet but it’s been different every time. in nocturne there were dialogue flags throughout to either unlock/lock each ending, and if you flagged multiple you choose at the end
in smtiv you collected law/chaos “points” througout, and they determine it at the end

@samgyeopsaI_ the series is really good at presenting situations in a really neutral and objective way so you can make your choices yourself! you’re just dropped into the world and they ask “what would YOU do?” it feels like *you* are the protagonist since your choices change the outcome

@samgyeopsaI_ alignment when making your final decision, which is why there’s usually minimal character development, so you don’t get too biased. i find the mainline smt games super entertaining and interesting personally, but totally understand why others don’t

@samgyeopsaI_ that’s fair! as someone who plays games for story/plot i still really love smt because it gives enough information for us to interpret while still withholding enough information to let us make our own decisions. it’s intentional so you don’t get swayed into any particular ->

@samgyeopsaI_ plot is always minimal in mainline smt games, if you put all the cutscenes in nocturne together it’d probably be less than an hour total. the focus is on gameplay with a generally unsettling world/atmosphere, and leaves a lot of shit like morality up to the player to interpret

@djinr8 a lot of cons run as nonprofits because it gets them cheaper venue rates and means they dont have to pay taxes as long as the money they make goes back into the “organization”, which they then use to pay for the venue/hire guests. but it also means they run at super thin margins

@djinr8 it Shouldn’t be legal but technically you’re paying “membership fees” for an organization you’re joining for one weekend. unlike something like a concert ticket, which owes you a refund if the concert is cancelled or the option for a refund if it’s postponed

@djinr8 cons can get away with shady shit because most of them are nonprofits and instead of selling tickets they sell “memberships” that just so happen to allow you into the convention space. you don’t buy a ticket you pay a “membership fee” so it opens up a lot of financial loopholes

it feels like a really strange writing decision, like they were purposefully trying to force the true ending to be worse than the bad ending because life cant always be happy. but you can do that without taking out the charm and the heartwarming moments and camaraderie of persona

and unnatural can be good, subversive can be good, but this just felt lame. there’s no reason you couldn’t have watched your friends graduate, there’s no reason everyone had to move away, there’s no reason you couldn’t have at least been asked by sojiro to stay living there.

you leave alone without so much as a “friends all seeing you off on the train platform” moment a la persona 4. it feels like they dont care about letting you, or the group, go. they say a quick goodbye and scatter to the wind. it feels very unnatural for a persona game.

the scene where they all drive you home is obviously fun and heartwarming, but still emotional because you know it has to end. the game starts with you arriving alone and outcasted and the vanilla ending has you leave surrounded by the people you love most. the royal ending has

persona, which is those interpersonal relationships, especially within the core group of each game. that message is still there because YOU are moving home, they don’t need to move too. i’m really bothered about the true ending being you going home alone on the train because

on the flip side the true ending has the weird addition of everyone deciding to move away, which i assumed was just to hammer in the “everyone is going their separate ways but theyll all care about each other and stay friends” message, but it takes away what people love about

if you had transplanted those scenes into the true ending and taken akechi out, they would have made sense and been a nice heartwarming resolution. the only things that make them obviously “not real” are akechi being alive, sumire being kasumi, and you ACKNOWLEDGING THE SITUATION

the scenes that take place in the bad ending (hanging out with your friends at leblanc, sojiro asking you to move in permanently, and celebrating the third years’ graduation) are not things that couldn’t exist in the true ending. they’re not unrealistic or unreasonable.
i watched the cutscene for the bad ending and i literally prefer it over the true ending, not because its happier but because it makes more sense lmao

new years reflection time, i guess
